WEBVTT

00:00:00.733 --> 00:00:05.333
In 1891, a famous illustrator

00:00:05.800 --> 00:00:07.500
and German traveler

00:00:07.700 --> 00:00:08.900
Rudolf Cronau

00:00:09.133 --> 00:00:12.700
traveled to Santo Domingo to the home of the Cambiaso family

00:00:12.966 --> 00:00:14.100
and had the opportunity

00:00:14.800 --> 00:00:18.866
to observe and draw the cotton cemí in person

00:00:19.066 --> 00:00:21.000
including this illustration

00:00:21.933 --> 00:00:24.266
in his famous volume "Amerika"

00:00:24.933 --> 00:00:27.600
that same year, in 1891

00:00:27.933 --> 00:00:28.900
the archaeologist

00:00:29.733 --> 00:00:31.700
American Jessie Fewkes

00:00:32.166 --> 00:00:35.300
published an article in American Anthropologist

00:00:35.466 --> 00:00:37.400
dedicated to the cemíes of Santo Domingo

00:00:37.800 --> 00:00:39.933
in this article he included a drawing

00:00:40.766 --> 00:00:42.866
representing the two cemíes

00:00:42.966 --> 00:00:45.266
the cotton cemí and the wooden cemí

00:00:45.466 --> 00:00:46.266
now preserved

00:00:46.400 --> 00:00:49.000
at the Museum of Anthropology and Ethnography

00:00:49.166 --> 00:00:50.533
of the University of Turin

00:00:51.066 --> 00:00:52.800
these drawings were created

00:00:53.066 --> 00:00:55.100
based on an illustration

00:00:56.000 --> 00:00:58.800
made by a Dominican artist

00:00:59.366 --> 00:01:01.766
named Abelardo Rodríguez

00:01:02.100 --> 00:01:02.900
Urdaneta

00:01:03.600 --> 00:01:09.000
Fewkes would travel to Santo Domingo in person in 1902

00:01:09.766 --> 00:01:14.700
he went to the Cambiaso home to see the cotton cemí

00:01:14.900 --> 00:01:15.900
but did not find it

00:01:16.300 --> 00:01:17.200
in his diary

00:01:17.700 --> 00:01:22.400
he noted that the Cambiaso family had sent the cemíes to Italy
